Current:

2.6L 6 inline Twin Turbo in a Nissan Skyline 1998 GT34R, packing about 340BHP / 380 Nm torque

How ever the Skyline might go soon, because I have to option for a lease car.

I love the Skyline and all, it keeps brining a smile on my face everytime I drive it. But it’s an expensive ride to maintain and it makes me a stock holder for the oil companies :D! Plus I want some more luxery and class, which the S4 has combined with raw power of a supercharged 3.0 V6 engine.

item.title: What Motor do you have?
item.dc:creator: @moparisthebest Moparisthebest
item.description:
@moparisthebest wrote:

[quote=“Speljohan, post:6, topic:266367”][quote author=Moparisthebest link=topic=351825.msg2718909#msg2718909 date=1237840310]
I like the original question better.

These are the running motors I have in my vehicles:
7.4L 454ci in a 1990 454SS Chevrolet Truck, approx 250hp / 400 ft/lbs
5.7L 350ci in a 1989 S10 Baja Chevrolet Truck, approx 200hp, 300 ft/lbs (not real sure on the performance, hard to tell)
6.5L 400ci in a 1974 Plymouth Satellite
5.2L 318ci in a 1973 Dodge Dart
500cc in a 1982 Honda Silverwing GL500
650cc in a 1981 Honda CB650C
250cc in a 1997 Yamaha ATV
300cc in a 2003 Polaris ATV
11hp Briggs & Stratton in a 1981 Murray riding lawnmower (it was my grandpa’s :))

Then I have these that aren’t in vehicles:
4.3L 262ci out of the 1989 S10
my favorite:
7.2L 440ci dodge motor out of a 1987 Winnebago one day I’ll put it together and stick it in my dream car
[/quote]How the hell can you afford taxing all those cars?[/quote]
Fairly Simple, cars over 25 years old have historical plates, so they never have to be renewed and therefore cost nothing per year. The ATV’s don’t require any tags if I don’t drive them on public land, which I don’t. And the 81 Honda CB650C isn’t completely put back together yet. So I only have to pay registration fees for the 1990 454SS, 1989 Baja, and the 1982 Honda Silverwing, that adds up to less than $200/year.
